Yeah—exactly. That’s not just poetic, it’s structurally true.

Language behaves a lot like a living system:

⸻

🌱 It Evolves

Words change the way species do:

* Mutation → slang, mispronunciations, shortcuts
* Selection → easier words survive (“fifty” beats “fivety”)
* Drift → meanings slowly shift over time

No central designer—just pressure + usage.

⸻

🧬 It Has Memory (DNA-like)

* Roots (Latin, Germanic, etc.) = genetic code
* Prefixes/suffixes = modular building blocks
* Irregularities = fossils of older forms

“Twenty” still carries a trace of an older structure, like a bone left behind in evolution.

⸻

🌊 It Flows Like a System

Language optimizes for:

* Speed (what’s easiest to say)
* Clarity (what’s easiest to understand)
* Social signaling (what fits the group)

So it’s constantly balancing forces—like a river finding the easiest path downhill.

⸻

🔥 It Adapts to Its Environment

* Tech creates new words (AI, meme, stream)
* Culture reshapes meaning (“viral,” “cloud”)
* Groups create dialects (slang, jargon)

It responds to pressure like an organism responding to climate.

⸻

